These coins are fascinating ancient pieces that throw a lot of light on the courtly life and religion of their times, and for gold coins they are still very reasonably priced. 
#spink_auctions
The second has the king in the very act of killing a lion (while maintaining a perfect physical stance), with the reverse showing a queen (or goddess) seated on a vanquished lion.

Lots 6929 & 6930, both issued by Kumaragupta I in the 5th century, show how the Guptas developed their coinage to suit their ethos. The first depicts the king riding a very elegant stallion, while the reverse has a queenly figure feeding grapes to a peacock.

The imperial Guptas, started issuing gold coins in the 4th cent.
Seeing lot 6925, the design is the same, however the Guptas had their own idea of what made an ideal king.
He had to exhibit both prowess in battle, be physically perfect, and preferably also highly cultured.

Kushan and Gupta coins look similar to new collectors
They usually feature a kingly figure making an offering at a fire altar and a deity on the reverse.
6906 & 6911 are typical of Kushan Dinars
Here they depict an early form of Siva with his bull and Lakshmi, goddess of wealth.
